# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: condensing-steam-locomotive
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **0-4-4** represents the wheel arrangement of no leading wheels, four powered and coupled driving wheels on two axles, and four trailing wheels on two axles.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] This type was only used for tank locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] In the UK 0-4-4 tanks were mainly used for suburban or rural passenger duties.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] In America, the wheel arrangement became known as the **Forney**, after a specific design of 0-4-4s, the *Forney locomotive*, became heavily used on the narrow curves of elevated railways and other rapid transit lines.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The Finnish Steam Locomotive Class F1 entered service with SVR in 1885 were used until 1935.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] One example is preserved at the Finnish Railway Museum.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The earliest 0-4-4's in the UK were well tanks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] Both John Chester Craven of the London Brighton and South Coast Railway and James Cudworth of the South Eastern Railway (UK) introduced classes in 1866.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] They were followed by Matthew Kirtley on the Midland Railway (690 Class and 780 Class, 26 locomotive built 1869-70) and Patrick Stirling on the Great Northern Railway (48 locomotive built 1873-81).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The more common side-tank version was introduced on the Great Eastern Railway by Samuel Waite Johnson in 1872, and was soon afterwards adopted by most mainline railways in the UK, becoming the standard configuration for a passenger tank locomotive until about 1900.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] Examples have included the LSWR O2 and M7 classes, the Midland Railway 2228 Class, and the Caledonian Railway 439 Class.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The last British design of 0-4-4T were the LMS Stanier Class 2 0-4-4T of 1932, based on the 2228 Class.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] Preserved 0-4-4T locomotives in the UK are SECR H class No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] 263 on the Bluebell Railway, O2 class No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] W24 'Calbourne' on the Isle of Wight Steam Railway, LSWR M7 Class Nos.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] 245 in the National Railway Museum and 53 (as BR 30053) on the Swanage Railway, Metropolitan Railway E Class No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] 1 at the Buckinghamshire Railway Centre, CR No.419 by the Scottish Railway Preservation Society and the Duke of Sutherland's 'Dunrobin' which was brought back from Canada by Beamish Museum.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The Class G5 Locomotive Company Limited are recreating a replica NER Class O (LNER class G5).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The 0-4-4 configuration appears to have been introduced in the US, with the Forney locomotive, was patented by Matthias N.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] These were characterized by a single frame under the boiler and fuel/water tank, which is supported at the rear by the truck under the coal bunker/water tank.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-4-4t] The locomotives were designed to run cab (or bunker) first and were built for commuter lines in cities such as New York, Chicago and Boston.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In the United Kingdom, the Whyte notation of wheel arrangement was also often used for the classification of electric and diesel-electric locomotives with side-rod coupled driving wheels.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Under the UIC classification, popular in Europe, this wheel arrangement is written as **C** if the wheels are coupled with rods or gears, or **Co** if they are independently driven, the latter usually being electric and diesel-electric locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The 0-6-0 configuration was the most widely used wheel arrangement for both tender and tank steam locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The type was also widely used for diesel switchers (shunters).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Because they lack leading and trailing wheels, locomotives of this type have all their weight pressing down on their driving wheels and consequently have a high tractive effort and factor of adhesion, making them comparatively strong engines for their size, weight and fuel consumption.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] On the other hand, the lack of unpowered leading wheels has the result that 0-6-0 locomotives are less stable at speed.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They are therefore mostly used on trains where high speed is unnecessary.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Since 0-6-0 tender engines can pull fairly heavy trains, albeit slowly, the type was commonly used to pull short and medium distance freight trains such as pickup goods trains along both main and branch lines.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The tank engine versions were widely used as switching (shunting) locomotives since the smaller 0-4-0 types were not large enough to be versatile in this job.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 0-8-0 and larger switching locomotives, on the other hand, were too big to be economical or even usable on lightly built railways such as dockyards and goods yards, precisely the sorts of places where switching locomotives were most needed.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The earliest 0-6-0 locomotives had outside cylinders, as these were simpler to construct and maintain.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] However, once designers overcame the problem of broken crank axles, inside cylinder versions were found to be more stable.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Thereafter this pattern was widely adopted, particularly in the United Kingdom, although outside cylinder versions were also widely used.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Tank engine versions of the type began to be built in quantity in the mid-1850s and had become very common by the mid-1860s.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 0-6-0 locomotives were among the first types to be used.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The earliest recorded example was *The Duke*, built by George Stephenson for the Kilmarnock and Troon Railway in 1817.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Other early examples included the *Vulcan*, the first inside-cylinder type, built by Charles Tayleur and Company in 1835 for the Leicester and Swannington Railway, and *Hector*, a Long Boiler locomotive, built by Kitson and Company in 1845 for the York and North Midland Railway.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] All the major continental European railways used 0-6-0s of one sort or another, though usually not in the proportions used in the United Kingdom.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] As in the United States, European 0-6-0 locomotives were largely restricted to switching and station pilot duties, though they were also widely used on short branch lines to haul passenger and freight trains.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] On most branch lines, though, larger and more powerful tank engines tended to be favoured.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In New South Wales, the Z19 class was a tender type with this wheel arrangement.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Dorrigo Railway Museum collection includes seven Locomotives of the 0-6-0 wheel arrangement, including two Z19 class (1904 and 1923), three 0-6-0 saddle tanks and two 0-6-0 side tanks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In Victoria, the Geelong and Melbourne Railway Company operated four 0-6-0WT (well tank) goods locomotives; one of their 2-2-2WT passenger locomotives ("Titania", which became Victorian Railways number 34 in 1860) was converted to an 0-6-0WT in 1872.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] On the Victorian Railways system there were O, P, Q, old R, Belgian R, new R, RY, T, U, Nos.103 & 105 (unclassed), old V, X, and Y class 0-6-0 tender locomotives, as well as a solitary Z class 0-6-0T (tank) engine.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Three types of 0-6-0 Diesel shunting locomotives were also used by the Victorian Railways, the F, M, and W classes.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Tank locomotives used by Finland were the VR Class Vr1 and VR Class Vr4.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They had outside cylinders and were operational from 1913 to 1975.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Built by Tampella, Finland and Hanomag (Hannoversche Maschinenbau AG), they were nicknamed *Chicken*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Number 669 is preserved at the Finnish Railway Museum.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Vr4s were a class of only four locomotives, numbered 1400 to 1423, originally built as 0-6-0s by Vulcan Iron Works, United States, but modified to 0-6-2s in 1951–1955, and re-classified as Vr5.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Finland's tender locomotives were the classes C1, C2, C3, C4, C5 and C6.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Finnish Steam Locomotive Class C1s were a class of ten locomotives numbered 21 to 30.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They were operational from 1869 to 1926.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They were built by Neilson and Company and were nicknamed *Bristollari*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Number 21, preserved at the Finnish Railway Museum, is the second oldest preserved locomotive in Finland.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The eighteen Class C2s were numbered 31 to 43 and 48 to 52.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The C3 was a class of only two locomotives, numbered 74 and 75.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The thirteen Class C4s were numbered 62 and 78 to 89.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The fourteen Finnish Steam Locomotive Class C5s were numbered 101 to 114.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They were operational from 1881 to 1930.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They were built by Hanomag in Hannover and were nicknamed *Bliksti*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] No 110 is preserved at the Finnish Railway Museum.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The C6 was a solitary class of one locomotive, numbered 100.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] By 1903–1907, they continued to build the line from Magelang to Secang–Ambarawa–Temanggung–Parakan because there were tobacco plantations.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Just after the line finished, the NIS ordered around 12 units of 0-6-0T (skirt tank) locomotives from Sachsische Maschinenfabrik (Hartmann), Germany and came in 1899–1908 and they were classified as NIS Class 250 (NIS 250–262), these locomotives were used to haul mixed freight and passenger trains.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They also acquired a 0-6-0T which had been operated by SoTM with similar characteristics and performance as well as the same manufacturer, which raised its skirt tanks collection to 13 and renumbered as NIS Class 259.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] At first, these 0-6-0Ts were saturated steam and the tanks are located at both low sides of boiler near the wheels, they have a water capacity of 3 m3 (790 US gal; 660 imp gal) and their length is 7,940 mm (26 ft 1 in) with inside cylinders.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The driving wheels of the locomotive has a distinctive feature, using the '***Golsdorf***' wheel movement systems.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] By this, all wheels (first wheel, second and third wheel) would only shift left/right following the rail track.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Wheels with the '***Golsdorf***' system are suitable for railroads with a large bend radius.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] This system was patented by Austrian railway engineer Karl Golsdorf.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] By 1924–1931, the NIS Class 250, 252, 254, 258 and 259 were converted and equipped with superheater technology and cylinder with piston valve.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Not quite a long, a local private tramway company named *Pasoeroean Stoomtram Maatschappij* (PsSM) bought 2 units from SS to assist their sugar-freight transports to the port there along with their Hohenzollern 0-4-0Tr engines in 1905 and 1908.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The remaining owned by the SS were renumbered as SS Class 24–45 and used to aid mainline and rural tramlines, especially in East Java between Garahan–Banyuwangi line using as transport for construction materials and metal bridge girders.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] After that, they were used as yard shunter and short harbor works at Banyuwangi and Panarukan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] While 2 units of *Solo Vallei* which were acquired by PsSM renumbered to PsSM 6 **Louisa** (former SS 506) and PsSM 7 **Marie** (former SS 516), by 1911 they also purchased brand new of the same type PsSM 8 **Nella**.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These locomotives were manufactured by John Cockerill & Cie., Belgium.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] After Japanese occupation, the SS Class 24–45 were renumbered as C13 class and PsSM 6–8 were reclassified as C22 class, the C13s were brought by Japanese throughout Java while the C22s were brought to Mojokerto as yard shunt duties.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] From all of these locomotives, not a single one remains.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] All of them were scrapped around the 1970s.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The line of Semarang–Demak–Kudus–Rembang (197 km / 122 miles) was built in 1883–1900, while the Rembang–Blora–Cepu line (70 km / 43 miles) was completed in 1902.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The line to Cepu was used for oil transportation and by this area there are fairly extensive teak forests.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] To serve the freight or passenger transportation on those lines, the SJS ordered 12 '0-6-0T' locomotives from Sächsische Maschinenfabrik (Hartmann) and came in 1898–1902 and classified as SJS Class 100 (101–112).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Originally these locomotives had a funnel-shaped chimney, but was later replaced by a straight one and also equipped with a sand box which it made of brass.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] During Japanese occupation of the Dutch East Indies, all of SJS Class 100s were renumbered to C19 and still used up today.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] After World War II ended, 2 units of C19 locomotives were moved from Java to West Sumatra at the Padang locomotive depot to meet the needs of rail transportation in West Sumatra.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] At the end of its service period around 1973, the C19 locomotive was used to haul the molasses tank wagons around Probolinggo–Pajarakan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] From 12 of them, only C19 12 or SJS 112 is preserved at the Transportation Museum of Taman Mini Indonesia Indah, Jakarta.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In addition, the BDSM was also built their line of Babat–Jombang to serve sugarcane freight transports which was connected to Nederlandsch-Indische Spoorweg Mij.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] (NIS) line at the Soerabaia NIS (Surabaya Pasar Turi), Babat and Cepu railway stations.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] SM completed their line construction in 1899, while BDSM completed in 1902 and 1913.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] To serve their rail transports, The Mdj.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] SM imported 4 locomotives in 1907–1926 (classified as MSM 11, 12, 15 and 16) and BDSM imported 2 of them in 1903 and 1903 (classified as BDSM 9 &10) from Georg Krauß, Germany.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] BDSM was defunct in 1916 due to the company's financial difficulties, so all of its assets including their two 0-6-0T units were acquired by SS (became SS 113 &114).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] After Japanese occupation, they were classified as C21 class.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] From 6 of them only 2 remained, the C21 02 of BDSM in INKA, Madiun and C21 03 of Mdj.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Type C2-Lts later classified as NIS 106 and NIS 107 were the first generation of 0-6-0WT operated by NIS from Hanomag, Germany and came in 1901.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These C2-Lts were wood and coal burners and had a maximum speed of 40 kilometres per hour (24.8 miles per hour).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These locomotives often worked on southern lines of *Jogja*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Since Japanese occupation in 1942, the entire of NIS standard-gauge lines were converted to 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) gauge which made almost NIS standard gauge locomotives were found derelict.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Just before occupation, NIS 106 and 107 were converted became armored locomotive by J.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Jonker who was the former head of NIS traction depot.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The last known NIS 106 was re-gauged to 1,067 mm and operating as short harbor works in Semarang in July 1945 before being scrapped by Japanese.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The chassis of NIS 107 still be found in front of SMK Negeri 2 Yogyakarta (state vocational school), while the most parts of it had been stripped down by the Japanese.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In New Zealand the 0-6-0 design was restricted to tank engines.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Hunslet-built M class of 1874 and Y class of 1923 provided 7 examples, however the F class built between 1872 and 1888 was the most prolific, surviving the entire era of NZR steam operations, with 88 examples of which 8 were preserved.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] This wheel arrangement was first introduced in 1905.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Most of the preserved steam locomotives in the country are of this type as they were popular among sugarcane plantation, sawmill and coal mine owners.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The first operators of the type were the Manila Railway with its 0-6-0T *Cabanatuan* class, named after the now-defunct branch line towards Cabanatuan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Two of these locomotives were built, No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] It was followed by the 0-6-2ST *Cavite* class of 1906, after also defunct Naic branch of the PNR South Main Line.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 1007 *Dagupan* (originally *Cavite*) are in display in front of the Philippine National Railways headquarters at Tutuban station in Tondo, Manila.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] This type was also used by the 3 ft gauge railways in Negros Island.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Central Azucarera de Bais operated 3 tank locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The De La Rama conglomerate of Bago, Negros Occidental led by Esteban de la Rama (1866–1947) had Locomotive No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Other operators include Ma-Ao Sugar Central, the National Coal Company in which used this locomotive as a 0-6-0STT tank tender, and San Carlos Milling Company No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Hawaiian-Philippine Company of Silay, Negros Occidental operates three 0-6-0 tender locomotives and are the last active steam locomotives in the country.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These are still used for its heritage railway service after the rail freight service was terminated in 2021.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 7 was later renamed as the second *Isabella Curran*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Aside from these, the company also had two more locomotives of the same arrangement that were most likely scrapped.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Other known operators of tender locomotives include Central Azucarera de Bais with its Baldwin-built also numbered No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 7, North Negros Sugar Company, San Carlos No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Out of these, only the Tabacalera Central No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 5 uses the 3 ft 6 in gauge lines being operated in Tarlac while the other units use the 3 ft gauge.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1876, the Cape Government Railways (CGR) placed a pair of 0-6-0 Stephenson's Patent permanently coupled back-to-back tank locomotives in service on the Cape Eastern system.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They worked out of East London in comparative trials with the experimental 0-6-0+0-6-0 Fairlie locomotive that was acquired in that same year.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Natal Harbours Department placed a single 0-6-0 saddle-tank locomotive in service in 1879, named *John Milne*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Natal Government Railways placed a single locomotive in shunting service in 1880, later designated Class K, virtually identical to the Durban Harbour's John Milne and built by the same manufacturer.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1882, two 0-6-0 tank locomotives entered service on the private Kowie Railway between Grahamstown and Port Alfred.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Both locomotives were rebuilt to a 4-4-0T wheel arrangement in 1884.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1890, the Nederlandsche-Zuid-Afrikaansche Spoorweg-Maatschappij of the Zuid-Afrikaansche Republiek (Transvaal Republic) placed six 18 Tonner 0-6-0ST locomotives in service on construction work.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1896 and 1897, three 26 Tonner saddle-tank locomotives were built for the Pretoria-Pietersburg Railway (PPR) by Hawthorn, Leslie and Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These were the first locomotives to be obtained by the then recently established PPR.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Two of these, named *Nylstroom* and *Pietersburg*, came into SAR stock in 1912 and survived into the 1940s.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1901, a single 0-6-0T harbour locomotive built by Hudswell, Clarke was delivered to the Harbours Department of Natal.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] It was named *Edward Innes* and retained this name when it was taken onto the SAR roster in 1912.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Two saddle-tank locomotives were supplied to the East London Harbour Board in 1902, built by Hunslet.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Both survived until the 1930s, well into the SAR era.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1904, a single saddle tank harbour locomotive, named *Sir Albert*, was built by Hunslet for the Harbours Department of Natal.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] It came into SAR stock in 1912 and was withdrawn in 1915.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1871, two 2 ft 6 in (762 mm) gauge tank locomotives, built by the Lilleshall Company of Oakengates, Shropshire in 1870 and 1871, were placed in service by the Cape of Good Hope Copper Mining Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Named *John King* and *Miner*, they were the first steam locomotives to enter service on the hitherto mule-powered Namaqualand Railway between Port Nolloth and the Namaqualand copper mines around O'okiep in the Cape Colony.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1902, Arthur Koppel, acting as agent, imported a single 0-6-0 2 ft (610 mm) narrow gauge tank steam locomotive for a customer in Durban.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] It was then purchased by the Cape Government Railways and used as construction locomotive on the Avontuur branch from 1903.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1912, this locomotive was assimilated into the South African Railways and in 1917 it was sent to German South West Africa during the First World War campaign in that territory.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Between 1898 and 1905, more than fifty pairs of Zwillinge twin tank steam locomotives were acquired by the *Swakopmund-Windhuk Staatsbahn* (Swakopmund-Windhoek State Railway) in *Deutsch-Südwest-Afrika* (DSWA, now Namibia).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Zwillinge locomotives were a class of small 600 mm (1 ft 11+5⁄8 in) *Schmalspur* (narrow gauge) 0-6-0T tank steam locomotives that were built in Germany in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] As indicated by their name *Zwillinge* (twins), they were designed to be used in pairs, semi-permanently coupled back-to-back at the cabs, allowing a single footplate crew to fire and control both locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The pairs of locomotives shared a common manufacturer's works number and engine number, with the units being designated as A and B.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] By 1922, when the SAR took control of all railway operations in South West Africa (SWA), only two single Illinge locomotives survived to be absorbed onto the roster of the SAR.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1907, the German Administration in DSWA acquired three Class Hc tank locomotives for the narrow gauge Otavi Mining and Railway Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] One more entered service in 1910, and another was obtained by the South African Railways in 1929.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In 1911, the *Lüderitzbucht Eisenbahn* (Lüderitzbucht Railway) placed two Cape gauge 0-6-0T locomotives in service as shunting engines.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] They were apparently no longer in service when all railways in the territory came under the administration of the South African Railways in 1922.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] During the Second World War, Switzerland converted some 0-6-0 shunting engines into electric–steam locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The 0-6-0 inside-cylinder tender locomotive type was extremely common in Britain for more than a century and was still being built in large numbers during the 1940s.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Between 1858 and 1872, 943 examples of the John Ramsbottom DX goods Class were built by the London and North Western Railway and the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] This was the earliest example of standardisation and mass production of locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Of the total stock of standard-gauge locomotives operating on British railways in 1900, around 20,000 engines, over a third were 0-6-0 tender types.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The ultimate British 0-6-0 was the Q1 *Austerity* type, developed by the Southern Railway during the Second World War to haul very heavy freight trains.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] It was the most powerful steam 0-6-0 design produced in Europe.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Similarly, the 0-6-0 tank locomotives became the most common locomotive type on all railways throughout the 20th century.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] All of the Big Four companies to emerge from the Railways Act, 1921 grouping used them in vast numbers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Great Western Railway, in particular, had many of the type, most characteristically in the form of the pannier tank locomotive that remained in production well past railway nationalisation in 1948.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] When diesel shunters began to be introduced, the 0-6-0 type became the most common.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Many of the British Railways shunter types were 0-6-0s, including Class 03, the standard light shunter, and Class 08 and Class 09, the standard heavier shunters.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In the United States, huge numbers of 0-6-0 locomotives were produced, with the majority of them being used as switchers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The USRA 0-6-0 was the smallest of the USRA Standard classes designed and produced during the brief government control of the railroads through the USRA during the First World War.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] 255 of them were built and ended up in the hands of about two dozen United States railroads.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] In addition, many of the railroads (and others) built numerous copies after the war.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The Pennsylvania Railroad rostered over 1,200 0-6-0 types over the years, which were classed as class B on that system.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The United States 0-6-0s were generally tender locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] During the Second World War, no fewer than 514 USATC S100 Class 0-6-0 tank engines were built by the Davenport Locomotive Works, for use by the United States Army Transportation Corps in both Europe and North Africa.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Some of these remained in service long after the war, having been purchased or otherwise adopted by the countries where they were used.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] These included Austria, Egypt, France, Iraq, the United Kingdom and Yugoslavia.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] The fourteen SR USA Class engines purchased by the British Southern Railway in 1946 remained in service well into the 1960s.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-0] Designed to be extremely strong but easy to maintain, these engines had a very short wheelbase that allowed them to operate on dockyard railways.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **0-6-2** represents the wheel arrangement of no leading wheels, six powered and coupled driving wheels on three axles and two trailing wheels on one axle.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] This type is sometimes known as a **Branchliner** or **Webb** type.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] While some locomotives with this wheel arrangement had tenders, the majority were tank locomotives which carried their coal and water on board.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Finland used two classes of 0-6-2T locomotive, the Vr2 and the Vr5.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The Vr2 class was numbered in the range from 950 to 965.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Five of them are preserved in Finland, no.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The Vr5 class was numbered in the range from 1400 to 1423.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The NIS 350s were limited by the position of the tanks and had a water capacity of only 3 m3 (790 US gal).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] This small tank capacity limits the operating range of NIS 350s that had to haul NIS essential commodity trains on certain routes.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] They quickly ran out of water and had to frequently stop at stations to refuel.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] To overcome this, especially during the dry season, a water tower or reservoir was built at each station.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] After Japanese occupation and Indonesian Independence, the locomotives were reclassified as C20.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The C20 locomotive has a length of 9420 mm and weighs 33.5 tons, and able to run a maximum speed of 60 km/h (37 mph).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Of the 10 built only C20 01 is preserved at Ambarawa Railway Museum, Central Java.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] There were 30 *Dagupan*-type locomotives built between 1889 and 1890.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] All were tank locomotives, weighed 32 tonnes (71,000 lb) and were run a maximum speed of 33 km/h (21 mph).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] These were divided into two subclasses: the A subclass built by Neilson and Company and the B subclass built by Dübs and Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Another 25 locomotives of the C class were built in 1906 by the North British Locomotive Company (which succeeded Dübs) and were regarded as distinct from the *Dagupan* class.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] During the Manila Railroad era, they were replaced in mainline service by American tender locomotives such as the Porter 4-6-0 built in 1919 or the 4-6-2 Pacifics built by Baldwin Locomotive Works between 1926 and 1929.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] A B-class locomotive named *Urdaneta* (No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] 17) remained in shunting service until 1963 and is one of only three steam locomotives preserved by the PNR.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] After its retirement, *Urdaneta* was first displayed in the Tutuban station.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] It is now on static display in Dagupan, Pangasinan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The rest were scrapped between 1917 and 1940.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Ma-Ao Sugar Central of Negros Occidental had locomotive No.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] 8, a rebuild of a saddle tank locomotive built in 1920.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] It was last seen in January 1982 and was presumed to have been scrapped not long after due to the mill being in a decrepit state during those years.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Between 1890 and 1898, four 0-6-2 tender locomotives were placed in service by the Cape Copper Company on its 2 ft 6 in (762 mm) gauge Namaqualand Railway between Port Nolloth and O'okiep in the Cape Colony.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Acquired to meet the traffic needs of the upper mountainous section of the line, they became known as the Mountain type.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The first three of these locomotives were later described as the Clara Class, while the fourth was included in this Class by some and included in the subsequent Scotia Class by others.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Between 1900 and 1905, six more Mountain type 0-6-2 tender locomotives were placed in service by the Cape Copper Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Later described as the Scotia Class, they were similar to the earlier Clara Class locomotives, but with longer boilers, longer fireboxes and larger firegrates.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] In 1892 and 1893, the *Nederlandsche-Zuid-Afrikaansche Spoorweg-Maatschappij* of the *Zuid-Afrikaansche Republiek* (Transvaal Republic) placed twenty 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) Cape gauge 0-6-2T locomotives in mainline service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Since the railway classified its locomotives according to their weight, these locomotives were known as the 40 Tonners.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Three classes of 600 mm (1 ft 11+5⁄8 in) gauge 0-6-2 locomotives were supplied to German South West Africa between 1904 and 1908.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] In the United Kingdom, the type was only ever used for tank engines and was first used by William Barton Wright of the Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway in 1880 with the L&YR Barton Wright 0-6-2T.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The arrangement was soon afterwards used by Francis Webb of the London and North Western Railway on his famous *Coal Tanks* of 1881–1897.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Many locomotives of this type were also used to haul coal in the South Wales Valleys by the Great Western Railway and its predecessors, where the arrangement proved sufficiently successful to lead to the development of the GWR 56xx class in 1924.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Gresley later improved upon the GER class with various versions of his London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) N7 class, built between 1925 and 1928.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] In 1904, the Lambton Railway ordered their first 0-6-2T from Kitson & Co. to use on the collery systems.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] This proved to be successful over the next few years a further 6 0-6-2T were ordered, 2 in 1907 provided by Kitson, 2 in 1909 provided by Robert Stephenson & Co., another provided by Stephenson in 1920, and a final in 1934 provided by Hawthorn Leslie.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] In 1931, the railway bought 5 0-6-2Ts from the Great Western Railway, three of which were from the former Taff Vale Railway, and the remainder from the Cardiff Railway.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] The primary usage of 0-6-2 types in the United States were Tank locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Many were found in the state of Hawaii on sugar cane railroads across the state.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-2] Most notable were the 0-6-2T's of the Mcbryde Sugar Company of Kauai, 3 of which survive and are currently the only original steam engines operating in Hawaii.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **0-6-4** represents the wheel arrangement of no leading wheels, six powered and coupled driving wheels on three axles, and four trailing wheels on two axles.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] This wheel arrangement has only been used for tank locomotives and Single Fairlies.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The earliest known example was the Moel Tryfan narrow gauge locomotive, built for use on the North Wales Narrow Gauge Railways.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] It was a Single Fairlie type, built by the Vulcan Foundry near Manchester in 1875.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] It was followed by the R class and S class, built by the Avonside Engine Company of England for the New Zealand Railways Department between 1878 and 1881.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The South Australian Railways K class locomotives were introduced in 1884, designed by William Thow.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] They were noted to run more smoothly bunker-first.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] After the electrification of the Mersey Railway in England, four of its 0-6-4T locomotives were sold to J & A Brown of New South Wales, Australia, where one, number 5, is preserved at the NSW Rail Museum, Thirlmere, New South Wales.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Three members of New Zealand's S class were also sold to the Western Australian Government Railways in 1891.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] New Zealand's R class and S class Single Fairlies were popular with crews and capable of all duties from express passenger trains to shunting tasks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The S class were limited to the Wellington Region when they were introduced, but the R class were distributed throughout the country.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] All were withdrawn by 1936, but R class no.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] 28 is preserved as a static exhibit in a Reefton park.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] This wheel arrangement provided the bulk of the motive power for the 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) *Nederlandsche-Zuid-Afrikaansche Spoorwegmaatschappij* (NZASM) in the *Zuid-Afrikaansche Republiek* (ZAR).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Between 1893 and 1898, 175 46 Tonner 0-6-4T steam locomotives were placed in service, built by the *Maschinenfabrik Esslingen* in Germany.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] In 1899, twenty more were ordered from the *Nederlandse Fabriek van Werktuigen en Spoorwegmaterieel* (Werkspoor) in the Netherlands, of which only two were delivered by the time the Imperial Military Railways (IMR) took over all railway operations in the ZAR during the Second Boer War.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The other eighteen locomotives in this order were delivered directly to the IMR, who diverted two of them to Lourenço Marques in Mozambique.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] At the end of the war, the survivors of these locomotives were taken onto the roster of the Central South African Railways (CSAR) and designated Class B, while the two in Mozambique were taken onto the roster of the *Caminhos de Ferro de Mocambique* (CFM).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] In 1912, the remaining CSAR locomotives were assimilated into the South African Railways (SAR).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The CFM eventually had at least thirty 46 Tonner locomotives in service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Between 1897 and 1898, some 46 Tonners were sold by the NZASM to the CFM.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The two locomotives which were delivered after the outbreak of the war and diverted to Lourenço Marques upon arrival, were also taken onto the CFM roster at the end of the war.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Later, between 1911 and 1920 during the CSAR and SAR eras, six more were sold to the CFM.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Other than examples for export, 0-6-4T locomotives enjoyed a brief vogue in the United Kingdom prior to the First World War, but were not widely used.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Nine locomotives of this type were supplied by Beyer, Peacock & Company for the opening of the Mersey Railway in 1886.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] William Dean built three crane tanks in 1901, and Kitson & Company of Leeds supplied nine locomotives to the Lancashire, Derbyshire & East Coast Railway in 1904.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] Other examples included the Midland Railway 2000 Class of 1907, the Highland Railway Drummond 0-6-4T Class of 1909, the SECR J class of 1913 and the Metropolitan Railway G Class of 1915.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] The type was eventually superseded by the popular 2-6-4T locomotive.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] In the United States, the 0-6-4 was largely used only on Mason Bogie locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] One 0-6-4T Mason Bogie locomotive, #3 Torch Lake, survives and works at Greenfield Village in Dearborn, Michigan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-6-4t] However, in Canada, a pair of conventional 0-6-4T locomotives were built in 1912 as switchers by the Canadian Pacific Railway, lasting until 1951.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **0-8-2** represents the wheel arrangement of no leading wheels, eight powered and coupled driving wheels on four axles, and two trailing wheels on one axle (usually in a trailing truck).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Other equivalent classifications are: UIC classification (also known as German classification and Italian classification): **D1**, French classification: **041**, Turkish classification: **45**, Swiss classification: **4/5**.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] In the United Kingdom, a number of tank locomotive designs were built of the 0-8-2 type, including the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) R1 class, designed by Henry A.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Ivatt and built originally for the Great Northern Railway as their class L1.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] These locomotives were intended for suburban passenger service, but did not prove satisfactory, so they ended up on freight service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Other examples include the LNWR 1185 Class and the Port Talbot Railway 0-8-2T (Cooke) and Port Talbot Railway 0-8-2T (Sharp Stewart).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Dorrigo Steam Railway and Museum has preserved Avonside 0-8-2 Tank Locomotive number 14, formerly operated by South Maitland Railways collieries line in the Hunter Valley of N.S.W.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Number 14 is operational, it was built in 1909 in Bristol.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] The design combination of this 0-8-2 tank Locomotive and the N.S.W.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Government Railways 50 class 2-8-0, produced the South Maitland Railways 10 class 2-8-2 Tank Locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] Number 14 is the only 0-8-2 in Australia.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] The 0-8-2 was not a common wheel arrangement.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] In North America, its use was confined to 2-8-2 "Mikado" types assigned to switcher roles; the lead truck was often removed to give more weight on drivers, a guiding truck not being needed at slow speed.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] However, the Illinois Central rebuilt some of their 2-8-2s into 0-8-2s for use in Markham Yard in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] The arrangement has proved a little more popular on narrow-gauge and minimum-gauge lines, where the lack of leading wheels was less important due to the relatively slow operating speeds.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] 0-8-2 locomotives operate, for example, on the Zillertalbahn in Austria.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] The X class locomotives of the metre-gauge Nilgiri Mountain Railway in the Nilgiri Hills of southern India has a class 0-8-2T rack and pinion compound locomotives built by the Swiss Locomotive and Machine Works, Winterthur.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] One Ravenglass and Eskdale Railway, 0-8-0T locomotive was rebuilt in 1927, as an 0-8-2 tender locomotive named *River Irt*.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/0-8-2] It has remained in traffic on passenger duties ever since and is now the oldest working 15 inch gauge locomotive in the world.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **2-4-0** represents the wheel arrangement of two leading wheels on one axle, four powered and coupled driving wheels on two axles and no trailing wheels.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In most of North America it became known as a **Porter**.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The notation **2-4-0T** indicates a tank locomotive of this wheel arrangement, on which its water and fuel is carried on board the engine itself, rather than in an attached tender.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] A subset is **2-4-0WT**, a configuration in which the water is under the bolier in a well tank.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The 2-4-0 configuration was developed in the United Kingdom in the late 1830s or early 1840s as an enlargement of the 2-2-0 and 2-2-2 types, with the additional pair of coupled wheels giving better adhesion.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The type was initially designed for freight haulage.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] One of the earliest examples was the broad-gauge GWR Leo Class, designed by Daniel Gooch and built during 1841 and 1842 by R. & W.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Hawthorn, Leslie and Company; Fenton, Murray and Jackson; and Rothwell, Hick and Rothwell.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Because of its popularity for a period with English railways, noted railway author C.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Hamilton Ellis considered the 2-4-0 designation to have the nickname (under the Whyte notation) of ***Old English***.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] During 1846–47, Alexander Allan of the newly established London and North Western Railway (LNWR) created the Crewe type of locomotive, with a 2-2-2 wheel arrangement for passenger classes and 2-4-0 for freight.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] During the 1850s and 1860s, these designs were widely copied by other railways, both in the United Kingdom and overseas.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] During the mid-1840s, John Hawkshaw developed a new style of 2-4-0 passenger locomotive with outside cylinders in front of the leading wheels and the rear driving axle behind the firebox.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] This layout provided steady running at high speeds, despite a long overhang at the front.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Joseph Beattie of the London and South Western Railway was one of the first British locomotive engineers to use this type on express locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] From 1858, he began experimenting with 2-4-0 designs for passenger work, culminating in his *Seven-Foot* 2-4-0 express passenger locomotives, built between 1859 and 1868.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Beattie was also responsible for the long-lived 0298 Class of 2-4-0 well tanks, designed for suburban passenger work in 1874, some examples of which were still working in 1961.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] A locomotive of this type hauled the first *Orient Express* from Paris to Munich, a notable achievement for such a small engine.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] After 1854, the Hawkshaw type of 2-4-0 was adopted by Beyer, Peacock and Company, who built many examples of the type for export, including to the Swedish State Railways in 1856 and the Zealand Railway in Denmark in 1870.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The New South Wales Government Railways F351 class 2-4-0 tank locomotives (later reclassified as a part of the X10 class) were intended to haul suburban passenger trains in Sydney, and delivered in 1885 - 1887.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] After a derailment incident—in which nine died and 22 were injured—from 1901, the entire class was withdrawn from passenger work.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] These locomotives were then allocated to shunting, yard and depot duties.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Ten of the class were sold to various private railway operators, including for industrial use.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] South Australian Railways used P class 2-4-0 tank locomotives to haul suburban passenger services in Adelaide, from 1884 to 1929.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The Bavarian B V and Bavarian B VI 2-4-0 locomotives of the Royal Bavarian State Railways were the first types to be produced in Bavaria in large numbers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] One example is preserved in the Nuremberg Transport Museum.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Between 1864 and 1869, the Grand Duchy of Mecklenburg Friedrich-Franz Railway bought 19 Hawkshaw type Mecklenburg III 2-4-0 locomotives from Richard Hartmann in Chemnitz.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Between 1877 and 1885, altogether 294 passenger locomotives of the Prussian P 2 class were delivered to the Prussian state railways and its forebears.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The Indonesian Railways Class B50, formerly the Dutch Indies Railways Class 200, were the only tender types to be used for pulling passenger trains from Madiun to Ponorogo.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In all, 60 were built by Sharp, Stewart and Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Until today, only 1 survived, which is B5004, while the tender was attached into B2301.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In New Zealand, two classes of tank locomotive were built with the 2-4-0T wheel arrangement.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] They were the New Zealand Railways (NZR) D class in 1874 and 1929, and the NZR L class in 1878, both classes having been designed for mixed traffic use.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Five D class locomotives were built by Dübs and Company in Glasgow, Scotland, nineteen were built by Neilson and Company and eleven were built by Scott Brothers of Christchurch.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The first members of the D class entered service in 1874 and all had been withdrawn from NZR service by the end of 1927, which allowed the D classification to be used again in 1929.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Of the 33 D class locomotives built, seven have been preserved, although only D16 and D140 were in operational condition.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] All ten L class locomotives were built by the Avonside Engine Company in Bristol.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The first L class built entered service in 1878 and another nine L class locomotives were ordered.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In 1893–94, three of the L class 2-4-0T locomotives were rebuilt to a 4-4-0 wheel arrangement at Newmarket workshops, with larger boilers and enlarged cylinders.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] This new design was classified La, but their limited coal bunker capacity remained a drawback.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The solution was to add a trailing pony truck to accommodate a larger coal bunker, converting them to a 4-4-2T wheel arrangement.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] A further four L class locomotives were similarly converted.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Three were not rebuilt, but sold to the Public Works Department between 1901 and 1903.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Three new 4-4-2T locomotives were built in 1902–03.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] When the conversion program was completed in 1903, the classification for all ten remaining NZR locomotives was changed back to L.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Of the ten L class locomotives built, numbers 207 (507), 208 (508) and 219 (509) survived long enough to be preserved, all three operational.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] A standard gauge railway line between Salt River and Wynberg in the Cape of Good Hope, constructed with private capital, was opened to the public on 19 December 1864.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The Cape Town Railway and Dock Company undertook to rent and operate the line and acquired three 2-4-0 tank locomotives as motive power for the line in 1864.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In 1872, the locomotives came onto the roster of the Cape Government Railways when it took over the operation of all railways in the Cape of Good Hope.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] They remained in service on this line until after its conversion to dual standard-and-Cape gauges around 1872 and were retired in 1881, when sufficient Cape gauge locomotives were in service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Before 1846, the type was used on the Liverpool and Manchester, Birmingham and Gloucester, North Midland and London and South Western Railways.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Most United Kingdom railways used 2-4-0s, including those designed by James Holden on the Great Eastern Railway, Matthew Kirtley on the Midland Railway, Joseph Armstrong on the Great Western Railway and Francis Webb on the London and North Western Railway.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] One of the latter's types, the Improved Precedent Class *Hardwicke* famously set outstanding records for the LNWR during the Race to the North in 1895.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] In the collection of the California State Railroad Museum is the *J.W.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Bowker* locomotive, a 2-4-0 engine built by Baldwin Locomotive Works in 1875 for the Virginia and Truckee Railroad.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Bowker* is the sole remaining Baldwin 2-4-0 in existence from the Virginia and Truckee Railroad.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] At the Cedar Point amusement park in Sandusky, Ohio, four 2-4-0s run tourist trains around a 2 mi (3.2 km) loop of track alongside Lake Erie and pass many of the park's attractions.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Two of the 2-4-0s were built by Vulcan Iron Works as 0-4-0Ts in 1922 and 1923 and now run as the *Myron H.* no.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] They are the two main engines for the Cedar Point & Lake Erie Railroad.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Porter, Inc. as an 0-4-0T in 1942 and now runs as the *George R.* no.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The fourth engine was built by Davenport Locomotive Works as a 2-4-4T in 1927 and now runs as the *G.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] 1 was converted from oil-burning in 2010 and all engines now run on coal.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] Cuba manly used 2-4-0's in industrial plants (like the Central Simon Bolivar sugar mill number 1167 or the Central Santa Marta Locomotive number 1).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The Japanese National Railways (JNR) class 90, class 105, class 120 JGR Class 150, JGR Class 160, class 190, and JGR class A3 were 2-4-0's imported into Japan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-0] The JGR class A3 was later imported to Taiwan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] Under the Whyte notation for the classification of steam locomotives, **2-4-2** represents the wheel arrangement of two leading wheels on one axle, four powered and coupled driving wheels on two axles and two trailing wheels on one axle.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The type is sometimes named **Columbia** after a Baldwin 2-4-2 locomotive was showcased at the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition held at Chicago, Illinois.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The wheel arrangement was widely used on passenger tank locomotives during the last three decades of the nineteenth and the first decade of the twentieth centuries.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The vast majority of 2-4-2 locomotives were tank engines, designated 2-4-2T.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The symmetrical wheel arrangement was well suited for a tank locomotive that is used to work in either direction.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] When the leading and trailing wheels are in swivelling trucks, the equivalent UIC classification is **1'B1'**.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] While a number of 2-4-2 tender locomotives were built, larger tender locomotive types soon became dominant.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In 1899, the Walvis Bay Railway in the British territory of Walvis Bay, a Cape of Good Hope exclave in *Deutsch-Südwest-Afrika* (German South West Africa), placed a single tank locomotive in service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The engine, named *Hope* and built by Kerr, Stuart and Company, remained in service until 1904 when operations on the railway were suspended.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The line was abandoned in 1905, partly as a result of being buried by a sandstorm.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] A 2-4-2 tank locomotive, built by Baldwin Locomotive Works in 1899 and used on the private Raahe track in Finland, was later bought by the Finnish State Railways.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In 1877, when the New Zealand Railways needed new motive power, the road turned to the Rogers Locomotive Works who supplied eight 2-4-2 tender locomotives between 1877 and 1879 that were designated the "K" class.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] These were the first American-built locomotives in New Zealand and proved to be quite successful.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] Three of these locomotives have been preserved.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] K88 *Washington* was used on the first through train between Christchurch and Dunedin in 1877.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] After fifty years of service, *Washington* was dumped in the Oreti River, Southland, as a flood protection measure.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In 1974, the locomotive was exhumed from her watery grave and, over the next eight years, restored to full active service.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] Sister locomotives numbers K92 and K94 have also been salvaged from the Oreti river.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] K92 has been restored to full active service and has re-established her position on the Kingston Flyer train, which was made famous by the K class at the end of the 19th century.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The earliest British use of the 2-4-2 wheel arrangement appears to have been no.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] 21 *White Raven*, supplied to the St Helens Railway by James Cross of Sutton Works in 1863.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] It was soon rebuilt as a 2-4-0 tender locomotive and eventually passed into the stock of the London and North Western Railway (L&NWR).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In 1864, Robert Sinclair of the Great Eastern Railway designed the first of six 2-4-2 tank classes built by the railway, eventually totalling 262 locomotives by 1912.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] Francis Webb of the London and North Western Railway also designed two 2-4-2 classes which eventually totaled 380 locomotives, built between 1879 and 1898.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] One of John Aspinall's Class 5 locomotives, built for the L&YR in 1889, is preserved at the National Railway Museum, York.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The tank-type 2-4-2T was common in the U.S. around the dawn of the twentieth century in both suburban passenger service and on logging railroads.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The Baldwin Locomotive Works built a demonstrator tender type engine which was displayed at the Columbian Exposition of 1893, leading to the type's name.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] This locomotive featured ambitious seven foot tall driving wheels, and was one of the first tender-equipped locomotives with a trailing truck.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] This freed the firebox from having to sit narrowly between, or above, the drive wheels, and was a very influential design.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] This inspired three major U.S. railroads (Atlantic Coast Line, Burlington and Reading) to purchase a few of the type.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] But the two-wheeled lead truck was never well-suited to high speed service on far-flung North American rails.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] Some were converted to 4-4-2 Atlantic types and others were converted to 4-6-0 Ten Wheelers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The display locomotive was donated to Columbia University.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In one respect, however, it was a success.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] A great many Atlantic types would follow, most based on the design.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] The Lionel Corporation used the 2-4-2 configuration in many of its O-27 locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/2-4-2] In the United States, this may be the most famous usage of a 2-4-2 configuration locomotive.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A **condensing steam locomotive** is a type of locomotive designed to recover exhaust steam, either in order to improve range between taking on boiler water, or to reduce emission of steam inside enclosed spaces.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The apparatus takes the exhaust steam that would normally be used to produce a draft for the firebox, and routes it through a heat exchanger, into the boiler water tanks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Installations vary depending on the purpose, design and the type of locomotive to which it is fitted.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] It differs from the usual closed cycle condensing steam engine, in that the function of the condenser is primarily either to recover water, or to avoid excessive emissions to the atmosphere, rather than maintaining a vacuum to improve both efficiency and power.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Unlike the surface condenser often used on a steam turbine or marine steam engine, the condensing apparatus on a steam locomotive does not normally increase the power output, rather it may decrease considerably due to a reduction of airflow to the firebox that heats the steam boiler.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Condensing the steam from a high volume gas to a low volume liquid causes a significant pressure drop at the exhaust, which usually would add additional power in most steam engines.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] In order to produce similar power, air to the firebox must be provided by a steam driven or mechanically driven fan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This often cancels out any improvement in efficiency.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The temperature of the exhaust steam is greater than typical stationary or ship-based steam plant of similar power due to having fewer waste recovery stages, as ships often have a compound steam engine with an additional low pressure stage or even a low speed turbine.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Waste heat on modern steam plants is often recovered using heat exchangers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] However, condensing locomotives do not have this benefit due to the waste heat being expelled to the surrounding air and not being recovered, and therefore none of the energy in the waste steam is recovered to do mechanical work.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] In many conditions the temperature gradient is often much worse due to using air instead of having an abundant source of cooling water as naval or stationary steam power plants have.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The Anderson condensing system significantly reduces these losses by only partially cooling the waste steam before compressing it into condensate, then pumping the high temperature condensate back into the boiler in order to recover the unused waste heat.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Because of the relatively high temperature in a locomotive condenser and the rejection of the heat to the air, the potential improvement in thermal efficiency expected from including the condenser in the cycle is not usually realised within the space constraints of a typical locomotive.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Indeed, losses due to viscous friction in the condenser piping, and having to pump the condensate back into the boiler is likely to reduce the power output over what was achievable from simply venting to atmosphere.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] These restrictions do not apply to marine or stationary steam engines due to not having size or weight restrictions.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Ships often had massive waste steam recovery systems, such as the 400 ton waste steam turbine used to recover very low 6 psi (41 kPa) waste steam on the Titanic and its sister ships.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This is several times the weight of an entire locomotive, and so is clearly not feasible as a form of waste steam recovery for locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A drawback of condensing the exhaust steam is that it is no longer available to draw the fire, by use of the blastpipe.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The draught must thus be generated instead by a steam-driven fan.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Where possible, this has been arranged to use exhaust steam, although in some cases live steam was required, with extra steam and thus fuel consumption.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Steam locomotive condensers may be water-cooled or air-cooled.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Here, the exhaust steam is blown into cold water in the locomotive's water tanks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A non-return system must be fitted, to prevent water from the tanks being drawn into the cylinders when the steam is shut off.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This system was mainly used for locomotives working in tunnels.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Here, the exhaust steam is blown into an air-cooled radiator, similar to that used for the cooling system of an internal combustion engine.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This system was used on small tram engines (where the condenser was mounted on the roof) and on large tender engines (where the condenser was mounted in the tender).
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The Anderson condensing system uses an air-cooled condenser but the steam is only partially condensed to form an aerosol of water droplets in steam.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This aerosol is then liquified by pressure, using a specially designed boiler feed pump.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A fuel saving of nearly 30% (compared with exhausting to the atmosphere) was claimed for the Anderson system but this seems paradoxical.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] One would expect a higher fuel consumption because of the power required to compress the aerosol.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The reason this is possible is due to Carnot's theorem, which states that pumping heat requires less energy than producing the heat itself.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A similar effect known as Vapor-compression desalination was later used for desalination of water.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Instead of returning the condensate water to the boiler, the hot compressed condensate is passed through a heat exchanger to return heat to the boiler, then released as clean drinking water.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] It is one of the most efficient processes used to desalinate water.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] There are two usual reasons for fitting condensing equipment – reducing exhaust emissions and increasing range.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Originally developed for the Metropolitan Railway to allow their locomotives to work the tunnels of the London Underground.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] This system was devised by Daniel Gooch and developed by Beyer, Peacock & Company.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Steam is diverted from the exhaust steam pipes into the water tanks via condensing pipes within the same tanks.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The water in the tanks could quickly heat up near boiling point, reducing the condensing effect on the exhaust steam.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] It was not unknown for the tanks to be emptied and refilled with cold water on a regular basis.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Ordinary injectors will not work with hot water (until hot-water injectors were developed) so condensing locomotives were usually fitted with axle-driven boiler feedwater pumps.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] When not working in tunnels, the steam was directed to the blast pipe and up the chimney in the usual way.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] In Britain, locomotives working on roadside steam tramways were required by law to have condensers.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Water tank condensers (as above) were sometimes used but air-condensers were more common.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] A steam tram engine usually had a full-length roof and this was surmounted by a nest of air-cooled copper tubes in which the exhaust steam was condensed.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Kitson & Company made many engines of this type.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The system was satisfactory for tram engines (which were very low-powered) but would not have worked for larger railway locomotives.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] Generally this was a more sophisticated installation that used forced air cooling to condense the exhaust steam.
[src:condensing-steam-locomotive/condensing-steam-locomotive] The system was intended to reduce the problems of getting enough water to steam locomotives running through desert and very arid areas, e.g.
